ing of the moment, their meeting was part of a global sea change in human relations and the nature of economic exchange. Brian P. Owensby uses the centuries-long encounter between Europeans and the indigenous people of South America to reframe the notion of economic gain as a historical development rather than a matter of human nature. Owensby argues that gain—the pursuit of individual, material self-interest—must be understood as a global development that transformed the lives of Europeans and non-Europeans, wherever these two encountered each other in the great European expansion spanning the sixteenth to nineteenth centuries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEconomicsxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aExchangezParaguayxHistory. 0aGuarani IndianszParaguayxHistory. 0aReciprocity (Psychology)zParaguayxHistory. 0aWhite peoplezParaguayxRelations with IndiansxHistory. 0aWhiteszParaguayxRelations with IndiansxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aEmpire.  aEuropean expansion.  aGift-Reciprocity.  aGlobalization.  aIndigenous Studies.  aIntellectual and cultural history.  aLatin America.  aMissions.  aMoral economy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073914540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362834240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503628342423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503628342/original  a978-3-11-073914-5  Stanford University Press Co